Defense in Depth is a layered cybersecurity strategy where multiple security controls are placed at different levels to protect systems.

Instead of relying on one security measure, multiple layers reduce the chance of total compromise.

Core concept:
If one layer fails, another layer continues protection.

For example, even if a phishing attack compromises credentials, MFA and Conditional Access may still block unauthorized access.

A real-life use case is enterprise cloud security.

Another example is government systems protecting sensitive infrastructure.

Defense in Depth creates resilient, overlapping security protections.
